Euphausia pacifica was the most abundant throughout the year off each coastal water, and their relative contribution to the total abundance of euphausiids was 89–92% (Table 1). Thysanoessa inspinata was the second highest in abundance off south‐eastern Hokkaido and Sanriku, and their relative contribution to the total abundance of euphausiids was 5–8%. Warm‐ and transitional‐water epipelagic species (corresponding to the Equatorial water group, the West North Pacific group excluding Stylocheiron suhmi, the West Pacific coastal group excluding Euphausia similis, and the Boundary group of Nemoto
36
) showed higher abundances off Joban than off the other two areas, and especially, Euphausia recurva, E. mutica, and E. tenera showed higher abundance among them.
